In a previous post, I talked about hosting a WebSocket server on IBM Bluemix.
With the help of a little Node.js on the server, and a browser in hand, we were
able to create a functional chat program. Since WebSocket is an open standard
however, we can talk to more than just the browser (despite the name). In this
post, I will show you how to create a native Android application that uses the
same WebSocket server to participate in a chat with the browser.

